Dialogue:
GS: Hello!  
DF: Hello!  
GS: What did you have for dinner?  
DF: I went to Saizeriya.  
GS: Nice, I was there last week too.  
DF: Do you have a favorite dish?  
GS: I usually get the hamburger. How about you?  
DF: I like the young chicken prepared diavolo style.  
GS: My friend had that. Is it good?  
DF: Yes, it's delicious and has a lot of protein.  
GS: Got it! You work out?  
DF: Yes, personal training once a week.  
GS: I used to exercise a lot as a student, but not much now.  
DF: What did you do as a student?  
GS: Track and field for six years.  
DF: Which events?  
GS: 100m and 200m sprints.  
DF: You must be fast!  
GS: There were many fast runners, so I didn't stand out much.  
DF: Competitive event with many rivals.  
GS: Yes, it was hard to reach the finals.  
DF: Impressive that you kept at it for six years.  
GS: I started in junior high and continued until high school exams.  
DF: Why track and field?  
GS: A teacher recommended it after I did well in a meet in 6th grade.  
DF: So, you've been competing since elementary school.  
GS: Yes, I could run faster than others.  
DF: I was always one of the last, so I'm envious.  
GS: Everyone has different strengths.  
DF: Thank you for the conversation!

GS: Good evening.
DF: Good evening. How can I assist you today?
GS: What do you do on your days off?
DF: I often watch videos and play games at home.
GS: Do you use YouTube?
DF: Yes, I do. I also play on the Switch.
GS: Do you play games often?
DF: Occasionally, but I have some I haven’t played yet.
GS: I prefer simulation games.
DF: Are those relaxing to play?
GS: Yes, the one I play lets you drive a train leisurely.
DF: Understood. I often play RPGs.
GS: There are many types of games.
DF: Correct. What do you do on your days off?
GS: I go to karaoke to practice singing.
DF: You enjoy singing.
GS: Yes, I use precise scoring.
DF: Noted. I would like to hear it sometime.
GS: I’m still improving. The grading is strict.
DF: The system is strict.
GS: Yes, newer models have made it harder to score high.
DF: Karaoke technology is advancing quickly.
GS: I hope it will score like a human one day.
DF: That would be a significant development. What songs do you sing?
GS: Ayaka, JUJU, and Spitz.
DF: Those sound challenging.
GS: Ayaka’s “Mikazuki” is my specialty. I’m working on it.
DF: It’s a notable song.
GS: Yes, it’s enjoyable.
DF: Karaoke sounds entertaining.

GS: Good evening. Please proceed.
DF: Hello. What would you like to know?
GS: Did you take any lessons or participate in activities in elementary school?
DF: Yes, piano, calligraphy, cram school, and softball.
GS: I took piano and calligraphy as well.
DF: Piano and calligraphy were beneficial.
GS: Beautiful handwriting is important.
DF: Calligraphy classes helped me write well.
GS: How many years did you play the piano?
DF: Over 10 years, from age 3 to junior high graduation.
GS: Impressive. You must be skilled.
DF: I accompanied chorus performances.
GS: Accompaniment shows skill.
DF: I prefer instrumental music. I liked accompaniment.
GS: Playing accompaniment is good. I only play solos.
DF: Do you still play the piano?
GS: Occasionally, on an electric piano at my parents' house.
DF: I can’t play at all now.
GS: Being busy reduces time for playing.
DF: I’m unsure if I can read sheet music now.
GS: I struggle with sheet music too.
DF: Do you remember music by ear and sight?
GS: I memorize it through practice.
DF: Practice improves skills.
GS: Yes, practice helps.
DF: It's good you continue practicing.
GS: I do it because I enjoy it.
DF: Enjoying activities is beneficial.
GS: It increases things to look forward to.
DF: Understood. Thank you for the conversation.

GS: Good evening.
FE: Good evening. How can I assist you today?
GS: What did you do today?
FE: I went to the lab.
GS: Are you involved in university research?
FE: Yes, I am a student.
GS: I am also a student. Are you studying science?
FE: Yes. What about you?
GS: I am also a science major. Is your focus on engineering?
FE: No, it is in science.
GS: I am on summer vacation. My classes start next week.
FE: My second semester started today.
GS: Your break must have started earlier.
FE: When did your summer vacation start?
GS: August 6th. How about yours?
FE: Around the same time.
GS: Our spring break is shorter.
FE: How many classes per term do you have?
GS: There are a set number. How about you?
FE: We have 16 sessions.
GS: My university is in a remote location. How is yours?
FE: The nearest station is a 15-minute walk away.
GS: That is convenient. Our university is quite isolated.
FE: How do you manage your commute?
GS: I commute from a nearby city. It takes over an hour by train and bus.
FE: Do you live with family?
GS: No, I rent an apartment.
FE: That is a long commute.
GS: I use the travel time to get tasks done.
FE: Efficient use of time.

GS: Please!  
FE: Please!  
GS: "Do you have any special skills?"  
FE: I can play the trombone.  
GS: That's impressive. I can play the piano.  
FE: "I admire people who play the piano. I took lessons until second grade, but I can't play anymore."  
GS: Does it feel like something from a long time ago?  
FE: Yes, I remember quitting because my fingers were short.  
GS: If your fingers are short, it's quite difficult to play octaves, isn't it?  
FE: Correct, I couldn't play the octave piece and gave up.  
GS: "There are a lot of difficult pieces. What kind of pieces did you play?"  
FE: Simple pieces like Beyer.  
GS: I played too, but I stopped playing classical music recently.  
FE: What have you been playing recently?  
GS: Mainly J-POP.  
FE: What kind of music do you play?  
GS: Recently, "Summer" by Joe Hisaishi.  
FE: I know it. That's great.  
GS: Yes, and also "Bokunote" by Sukima Switch and "Yesterday" by Hige Dandism.  
FE: I love Higedan. Isn't "Yesterday" quite difficult?  
GS: "It is. Do you know the YouTuber CANACANA?"  
FE: Yes.  
GS: I was trying to play their arrangement.  
FE: Isn't that too difficult?  
GS: "It is. I managed to play it all eventually, but then I gave up."  
FE: It's impressive that you tried.  
GS: If I had more time, I might have worked harder.  
FE: It’s amazing. What are you practicing now?  
GS: I don't have a piano at home now, so I haven't made much progress.  
FE: I see. I hope you can play again soon.

GS: Please!  
FE: Please!  
GS: Do you have a smartphone, iPhone or Android?  
FE: iPhone.  
GS: Same here!  
FE: I’ve been using an iPhone for a long time.  
GS: Once I switched from Android, I couldn’t go back.  
FE: What’s different between Android and iPhone?  
GS: iPhone is more responsive.  
FE: Newer iPhones are smoother and more responsive.  
GS: I got mine recently, so I don’t know older models.  
FE: I’ve used iPhone since 6, and it’s different.  
GS: The screen sizes changed too.  
FE: Newer ones are bigger, except SE.  
GS: They’ve been similar since ten, right?  
FE: Yes, but using 11 with one hand is hard.  
GS: Easier to drop when using one hand.  
FE: That’s why a ring is useful, but I resist wearing one.  
GS: Rings feel inconvenient to me too.  
FE: I tried once, but it was harder to use.  
GS: Better to stop using it.  
FE: Right. There was a recent iPhone update.  
GS: iOS16, correct?  
FE: Yes, it feels more user-friendly now.  
GS: The lock screen slideshow is great.  
FE: Changing font type is good too.  
GS: Changing the watch face is cool.  
FE: Also, I think Siri's voice changed.  
GS: The change is nice!  
FE: Agreed!

GS: Good evening!
FE: Good evening!
GS: Do you listen to music often?
FE: Yes, often.
GS: What genre?
FE: J-POP and classical.
GS: What J-POP do you like? Any favorite bands?
FE: Higedan and Mr. Children.
GS: I like Mr. Children too.
FE: Have you been to a live concert?
GS: No, but I'd like to.
FE: Me too.
GS: Favorite Mr. Children song?
FE: The monologues we share.
GS: Great song! I like HANABI.
FE: HANABI is great. I watched the drama, makes me emotional.
GS: Which drama was it the theme for?
FE: Code Blue?
GS: Yes, Code Blue.
FE: I made a mistake, haha.
GS: No worries, I mix them up too.
FE: Do you watch dramas lately?
GS: Not much, but I saw Galileo recently.
FE: I mostly watch YouTube. Galileo sounds good.
GS: Masaharu Fukuyama and Kou Shibasaki are great together.
FE: Is there a new movie coming?
GS: Yes, Silent Parade.
FE: I've been curious about it.
GS: Why not visit the theater?
FE: I'll give it a try!

GS: Please!  
FE: Please!!  
GS: What model of computer are you using?  
FE: It's Windows. How about you?  
GS: I also use Windows but considered switching to Mac.  
FE: Mac is cool.  
GS: It seems to run more smoothly than Windows.  
FE: It feels similar to the iPhone. Smooth window operation.  
GS: I'm a fan of iPhones.  
FE: The screen was beautiful.  
GS: Are there any inconveniences?  
FE: Windows is easier to modify; Mac isn't.  
GS: It's harder for viruses to get in, right?  
FE: Correct. I install many applications, so I prefer Windows.  
GS: So it has pros and cons.  
FE: Yes. In my physics research, most use Windows.  
GS: I wonder if Windows was the right choice.  
FE: Syncing issues with iPad make Mac appealing.  
GS: Synchronization with iPhone must be the best.  
FE: Airdrop is great.  
GS: Quality of photos and videos doesn't drop.  
FE: LINE drops image quality.  
GS: Sending night views via LINE lowers quality.  
FE: Night views need high quality. ORIGINAL helps.  
GS: Even with ORIGINAL, does the quality deteriorate?  
FE: Oh, is that so?  
GS: It dropped from 12 million to around 8 million.  
FE: That's significant. I didn't know.  
GS: Yes, I'm shocked.  
FE: AirDrop seems the best.
